The model employed in the study is termed the mechanistic population model of Ae. albopictus with diapause (MPAD). The model was developed by Jia et al. [25] to characterize the population dynamics of Ae. albopictus at different growth stages of its life cycle. The mosquito’s life cycle can be broadly dichotomized into the aquatic period and the aerial period with different compartments [33]. The MPAD model establishes a seven-stage life cycle, including eggs (diapause E
0 and non-diapause E
dia), larvae (L), pupae (P), emerging adults (A
em), blood-fed adults (A
b), gestating adults (A
g) and ovipositing adults (A
r). These stages are formulated by a set of seven differential equations to describe the successive development process of Ae. albopictus, as shown in Eq. (1). The parameters included in the equation are given in Table 1. In Eq. (1), the dependent variable of each differential equation denotes the daily variation of population abundance at a specific life stage. The climate-independent parameters in Table 1 are primarily driven by three climatic factors: daily mean temperature (T), daily accumulative precipitation (PP) and daily photoperiod (SD). Table 2 summarizes the relationship between these parameters and the climatic factors.Table 1
